2.1 Symbolic Regression and Equation Discovery

Symbolic regression (SR) is the task of finding mathematical expressions that best fit a dataset, without assuming a fixed model structure. Unlike traditional regression, SR explores a space of symbolic expressions, often represented as trees, to balance fit and complexity.

2.1.1 Early Developments

The roots of SR lie in genetic programming (GP), introduced by Koza [1] in the 1990s. GP evolves populations of expression trees using crossover and mutation operators, with fitness typically measured by mean squared error. Early successes included rediscovering physical laws from experimental data [2]. The Eureqa system [3] brought GP‑based SR to a broader audience, incorporating Pareto optimization between accuracy and complexity, and demonstrating rediscovery of classical mechanics equations.

2.1.2 Modern Symbolic Regression

Recent years have seen significant advances in SR efficiency and scalability:

· AI Feynman [4] uses neural networks to identify functional forms and recursively simplifies equations, achieving state‑of‑the‑art recovery on physics problems.
· PySR [5] implements a high‑performance GP framework with multi‑objective optimization and distributed computing, becoming a standard tool in the field.
· Operational research has explored Bayesian SR [6] and deep learning approaches for symbolic regression [7].

Despite these advances, most SR methods treat equations as generic mathematical expressions without incorporating physical prior knowledge such as dimensional homogeneity, symmetry, or conservation laws. This gap motivated the development of physics‑guided symbolic regression.

---

2.2 Physics‑Guided Symbolic Regression

Incorporating physical constraints into SR improves interpretability and reduces the search space by eliminating physically meaningless expressions.

2.2.1 Dimensional Analysis

Dimensional analysis ensures that equations are dimensionally homogeneous—a necessary condition for physical laws. The Buckingham π theorem [8] states that any physically meaningful equation can be expressed in terms of dimensionless groups. Several SR systems enforce dimensional constraints:

· PhySO (Physical Symbolic Optimization) [9] uses reinforcement learning to search for expressions, with a built‑in type system that checks dimensional consistency. It demonstrates superior performance on physics benchmarks.
· Units‑aware GP [10] assigns dimension vectors to terminals and propagates them through operators, pruning invalid expressions.

Our approach adopts a similar dimensional typing system but integrates it into a formal grammar that also encodes symmetry and conservation constraints.

2.2.2 Symmetry and Conservation Laws

Beyond dimensions, physical laws often obey symmetries (translational, rotational, gauge) and imply conservation laws (energy, momentum, charge). Incorporating these as constraints reduces the search space and improves discovered laws’ physical plausibility.

· Symmetry‑guided SR [11] uses group theory to enforce invariance under specified transformations.
· Lagrangian discovery methods [12] learn Lagrangians that automatically satisfy conservation laws via Noether’s theorem.

Our grammar allows explicit inclusion of symmetry operators (e.g., derivatives, rotations) and can enforce conservation by construction.

