2.4 Evolutionary Algorithms for Scientific Discovery

Evolutionary algorithms (EAs) have a long history in scientific discovery, particularly in equation discovery and inverse problems. This section reviews key developments and theoretical results.

2.4.1 Genetic Programming for Equation Discovery

GP for equation discovery typically uses tree representations and evolves populations of equations. Surveys by Tang et al. [17] and others document numerous applications in physics, engineering, and biology. Common operators include subtree crossover and point mutation, with fitness functions that penalize complexity to avoid overfitting.

2.4.2 Multi‑Objective Evolutionary Algorithms (MOEAs)

The trade‑off between accuracy and simplicity is naturally multi‑objective. NSGA‑II [18] is one of the most widely used MOEAs, employing non‑dominated sorting and crowding distance to maintain diversity. NSGA‑II has been applied to SR [19] and forms the basis of our selection mechanism.

2.4.3 Convergence Theory

Convergence properties of EAs have been studied extensively. For single‑objective EAs with elitism and ergodic operators, convergence to the global optimum in probability is established [20]. For MOEAs, convergence to the Pareto front is more subtle; however, under certain conditions (e.g., the archive of non‑dominated solutions is monotonically improving), convergence results exist [21]. We build on these foundations to prove convergence for our specific representation and operators.

2.4.4 Diversity Preservation

Premature convergence is a known challenge in EAs. Diversity preservation mechanisms include crowding, fitness sharing, and explicit distance penalties. Tree‑based populations can use structural distance metrics (e.g., tree‑edit distance) to maintain variety [22]. Our diversity proof relies on such a metric.

---

2.5 Formal Grammars and Type Systems for Physical Laws

Formal grammars provide a structured way to generate symbolic expressions. Context‑free grammars (CFGs) have been used in GP to enforce syntactic constraints [23]. Extending CFGs with typed terminals and dimensional constraints yields a powerful framework for generating physically meaningful expressions.

2.5.1 Typed Grammars

Typed grammars assign types (scalar, vector, tensor, spinor) to symbols and enforce type compatibility in operators. This prevents expressions that combine incompatible objects (e.g., adding a scalar to a vector). Our grammar extends typing to physical dimensions (mass, length, time, etc.), ensuring dimensional homogeneity.

2.5.2 Symmetry Operators

Symmetry operators such as derivatives, rotations, and gauge transformations can be included as primitives. Their properties (linearity, Leibniz rule) can be used to simplify expressions and guide search.

---

2.6 Multi‑Objective Optimization and Pareto Theory

Multi‑objective optimization deals with problems where two or more objectives conflict. The solution set is the Pareto front: all points where no objective can be improved without degrading another. In SR, accuracy (or negative likelihood) and complexity (e.g., number of nodes) are typically conflicting.

2.6.1 Pareto Optimality and Hypervolume

The hypervolume indicator measures the volume dominated by a set of solutions with respect to a reference point. Hypervolume maximization is a standard quality measure for Pareto fronts and is used in MOEAs like SMS‑EMOA [24]. We use hypervolume to track convergence.

2.6.2 Convergence to the Pareto Front

Under elitist selection (preserving the best solutions), MOEAs converge to the Pareto front in probability if the search operators are ergodic [25]. Our proof in Chapter 3 adapts this result to our grammar‑constrained space.

---

2.7 Gap Analysis and Positioning

Based on the literature reviewed, the following gaps are identified:

1. No provably convergent system for physical law discovery exists. All state‑of‑the‑art systems (Albert, Pixel2Phys, PhyE2E, NEXUS) rely on heuristics without formal guarantees.
2. Hybrid architectures are complex, opaque, and computationally expensive.
3. Existing pure evolutionary systems lack formal grammar constraints that enforce physical laws and do not provide diversity guarantees.
4. Comparative evaluation against recent breakthroughs is absent; no single study benchmarks pure evolutionary methods against the latest hybrids on common tasks.

This thesis addresses these gaps by proposing a pure evolutionary architecture with formal guarantees, grounded in a typed grammar that encodes physical constraints, and evaluated against the 2025–2026 hybrid systems on benchmark problems.

