6.6.1 Discovering the Friedmann Equation from Real Data

Using supernovae and Planck data, our method discovered an equation of the form $H^2 = \frac{8\pi G}{3}(\rho_m + \rho_{\Lambda})$, correctly identifying matter and dark energy components. The discovered $\Omega_m$ and $\Omega_\Lambda$ were within 5% of the Planck values.

6.6.2 Recovering the Harmonic Oscillator Hamiltonian

On simulated data, the method recovered $H = \frac{1}{2}(p^2 + \omega^2 q^2)$ exactly. With 10% noise, it found a slightly more complex expression but still with high predictive accuracy.

6.6.3 Higgs EFT: Detecting New Physics

In the EFT task with simulated new physics (dimension‑6 operator $O_{HG}$), our method correctly identified the need for an additional term in the Lagrangian, though the exact coefficient was biased due to limited data. This demonstrates potential for anomaly detection.

